&gt;&gt; The last movement?

00:41:40.590 --> 00:41:41.890
&gt;&gt; Yep.

00:41:41.890 --> 00:41:43.190
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:41:43.190 --> 00:41:45.760
&gt;&gt; Yeah there's some
similarities there that,

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:47.640
I think, are circumstantial.

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:52.390
But then there's,
let's see, yeah,

00:41:52.390 --> 00:41:54.680
so this sonata is well
worth getting to know,

00:41:54.680 --> 00:41:55.980
it's worth taking a look.

00:41:55.980 --> 00:41:57.280
You can just see
he's very much moving

00:41:57.280 --> 00:42:00.600
in a more modernist trajectory.

00:42:00.600 --> 00:42:03.780
The other pieces also, at
the time, were considered

00:42:03.780 --> 00:42:05.710
to be modernist as well.

00:42:05.710 --> 00:42:08.480
They really sound a bit
more familiar to us just

00:42:08.480 --> 00:42:10.400
because we've had the
innervating century

00:42:10.400 --> 00:42:14.210
to get used to those sounds.

00:42:14.210 --> 00:42:17.360
Let's see, I think, yeah,
last thing I think I have

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:19.670
on here is just kind

00:42:19.670 --> 00:42:21.910
of an interesting little
story about a piece.

00:42:21.910 --> 00:42:23.640
I don't have any examples of it

00:42:23.640 --> 00:42:27.170
because this is the piece that's
going to be premiered today.

00:42:27.170 --> 00:42:32.420
So, this is a version
of the central movement

00:42:32.420 --> 00:42:37.230
from Iberia Image for
orchestra Debussy.

00:42:37.230 --> 00:42:41.370
I'm not sure what did
that, but, anyway,

00:42:41.370 --> 00:42:45.590
so this is just the cover
page of the manuscript

00:42:45.590 --> 00:42:49.550
that he transcribed in 1915
after hearing the work.

00:42:49.550 --> 00:42:52.100
What's interesting is that he
didn't actually like the work

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:56.100
that much with the exception
of this one movement.

00:42:56.100 --> 00:42:57.670
So, he really took to it.

00:42:57.670 --> 00:43:00.640
Then, sorry for my washed
out photo here, but,

00:43:00.640 --> 00:43:06.210
you can see just that it's a
meticulously done transcription.

00:43:06.210 --> 00:43:10.420
And it's, Debussy himself did
not do a solo piano version

00:43:10.420 --> 00:43:11.720
of this work.

00:43:11.720 --> 00:43:15.260
But, Duran commissioned I think
Muran and the other people

00:43:15.260 --> 00:43:18.400
who have done solo
piano versions later

00:43:18.400 --> 00:43:23.320
that are much easier
to play than this one.

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:27.550
However, the difficulties
are worthwhile, I think,

00:43:27.550 --> 00:43:29.920
we'll see what you
think after hearing it.

00:43:29.920 --> 00:43:33.100
But, almost throughout
the entire work,

00:43:33.100 --> 00:43:35.350
he keeps it separated
onto three stage just

00:43:35.350 --> 00:43:38.680
to be able to keep voices clear.

00:43:38.680 --> 00:43:43.170
And so, that's one of the things
that's difficult to navigate

00:43:43.170 --> 00:43:45.150
but interesting to navigate.

00:43:45.150 --> 00:43:48.640
So, what's kind of
cool about this,

00:43:48.640 --> 00:43:52.700
and I hope that maybe you can
let people know about this as a,

00:43:52.700 --> 00:43:57.080
if you find this
interesting, is that I came

00:43:57.080 --> 00:44:00.540
across that transcription, that
manuscript when I was looking

00:44:00.540 --> 00:44:03.430
through just the
Griffes materials.

00:44:03.430 --> 00:44:06.120
And, I noticed, it was
catalogued, but I noticed

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:09.920
in the literature it said that
the piece was no longer extant.

00:44:09.920 --> 00:44:14.080
So, thought there was a
mistake, it was a mistake.

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:18.710
It in fact was extant, it
was existing right there.

00:44:18.710 --> 00:44:21.180
But, because of that,
nobody knew about it.

00:44:21.180 --> 00:44:24.010
And, that's why we're
doing, Solungga was willing

00:44:24.010 --> 00:44:25.930
to learn it and put it together.

00:44:25.930 --> 00:44:30.060
And so, I made this version
for her at first of the,

00:44:30.060 --> 00:44:32.760
an engraved form of it.

00:44:32.760 --> 00:44:35.430
And, what's kind of cool
about it is we're going

00:44:35.430 --> 00:44:39.800
to put this online and probably
as an attachment on the blog

00:44:39.800 --> 00:44:42.520
so that anybody who
wants to download it

00:44:42.520 --> 00:44:44.740
and play it themselves
can do so.

00:44:44.740 --> 00:44:47.630
So, we're hoping to do
that next week or so.

00:44:47.630 --> 00:44:49.840
But, so if you want to, if
this is something you want

00:44:49.840 --> 00:44:52.610
to just take a look at
yourself and play through,

00:44:52.610 --> 00:44:53.910
you're more than welcome to.

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:56.030
And so, it'll be
available that way.

00:44:56.030 --> 00:45:00.240
Yeah. And so, I think
I'm going to stop there

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:04.340
because that's the
end of my talk.

00:45:04.340 --> 00:45:05.640
But, thank you so
much for coming

00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:06.940
and I think you're going
to really enjoy it.

