I'm sorry, just to record it.

00:45:17.970 --> 00:45:19.270
Can you ask a question.

00:45:19.270 --> 00:45:23.590
&gt;&gt; You engraved that
right, that was my question.

00:45:23.590 --> 00:45:28.190
&gt;&gt; Yeah, yeah, that's it.

00:45:28.190 --> 00:45:31.510
Yeah. Anybody else?

00:45:31.510 --> 00:45:52.520
[ Inaudible ]

00:45:52.520 --> 00:45:56.460
Well that's a tough, I don't
know that I'm really equipped

00:45:56.460 --> 00:45:57.760
to answer that question.

00:45:57.760 --> 00:46:00.350
but, what I can say is that,
you know, that particular year

00:46:00.350 --> 00:46:04.470
that you're talking about
also had a pretty big impact

00:46:04.470 --> 00:46:07.770
on both this composer
and other composers,

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:12.520
especially Cesar Franck,
we're thinking of Tristan.

00:46:12.520 --> 00:46:16.640
And the emergence of that,
basically, I mean you can start

00:46:16.640 --> 00:46:22.140
to see changes in lots of
people's music that come right

00:46:22.140 --> 00:46:24.480
after their first hearing
it once they've got a chance

00:46:24.480 --> 00:46:26.360
to hear it.

00:46:26.360 --> 00:46:32.090
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] he was actually
[inaudible] produce a movie

00:46:32.090 --> 00:46:38.700
and when that boy [inaudible]
was exiled to Switzerland,

00:46:38.700 --> 00:46:41.170
he was hiking [inaudible],

00:46:41.170 --> 00:46:47.640
that's what influenced him
23 years later, [Inaudible].

00:46:47.640 --> 00:46:51.900
And, I'm sensing
these [inaudible] sort

00:46:51.900 --> 00:46:54.600
of seeing this recurrence.

00:46:54.600 --> 00:46:57.510
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I think I see where
you're going with that.

00:46:57.510 --> 00:46:59.500
The, what I can say
is that, I mean,

00:46:59.500 --> 00:47:01.430
really there's all
these major histories,

00:47:01.430 --> 00:47:04.880
especially literary histories
of the type of romanticism

00:47:04.880 --> 00:47:07.490
that goes into these
things coming at the turn,

00:47:07.490 --> 00:47:10.980
at the end of the 18th century
going into the 19th century.

00:47:10.980 --> 00:47:14.130
And, music starts to kind of
catch up with it and then kind

00:47:14.130 --> 00:47:18.130
of intermingle with it as the
century progresses in ever,

00:47:18.130 --> 00:47:21.270
you know, inventive ways.

00:47:21.270 --> 00:47:23.800
I actually don't think that
that every really stopped except

00:47:23.800 --> 00:47:27.310
for in certain types, you
know, Vanguard moves away

00:47:27.310 --> 00:47:33.250
from referential types of
music or art production.

00:47:33.250 --> 00:47:36.310
But, I think it's
right on to say that,

00:47:36.310 --> 00:47:38.810
especially at this time,
if you're looking at,

00:47:38.810 --> 00:47:41.160
I don't like the
term salon pieces

00:47:41.160 --> 00:47:43.490
because it's a bit diminutive.

00:47:43.490 --> 00:47:46.540
But, works that are character
pieces, maybe be a better,

00:47:46.540 --> 00:47:48.910
character works for a
solo piano that have a tie

00:47:48.910 --> 00:47:54.220
to a poetic source,
which, in turn is, usually,

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:58.340
some relation either
some love or nature,

00:47:58.340 --> 00:48:01.100
it's very much following
in that romantic path.

00:48:01.100 --> 00:48:04.830
And so, in that sense,
impressionism is romanticism.

00:48:04.830 --> 00:48:06.760
Everything, it's all,
all the isms just kind

00:48:06.760 --> 00:48:09.180
of blend together so.

00:48:09.180 --> 00:48:10.800
Sure, sure.

